WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.031
Here is how a biostatistician keeps a Smartsheet program tracker perfectly current without ever touching it, and without any A-I.

2
00:00:08.331 --> 00:00:13.767
On the left, a scheduled SAS or R job; on the right, the tracker it drives.

3
00:00:14.067 --> 00:00:22.495
The job writes the truthful operational status to the sheet by a stable key, and Smartsheet's own built-in workflow sends the alerts.

4
00:00:22.795 --> 00:00:26.630
Code owns the data; Smartsheet owns the notifications.

5
00:00:27.630 --> 00:00:35.512
This is the shipped library — plain, readable R, double-programmed and version-controlled like any study program.

6
00:00:35.812 --> 00:00:49.546
The flagship is one idempotent upsert: it matches every row by the Task code you own, updates the ones that already exist, and appends only the genuinely new — so re-running it converges to the same sheet.

7
00:00:49.846 --> 00:00:55.885
And before anything leaves the environment, a coded allowlist blocks any non-operational column.

8
00:00:56.885 --> 00:00:59.754
Beat one: the job reads the sheet first.

9
00:01:00.054 --> 00:01:09.008
It pulls a fresh column map — because the column ids are the only stable address — and reads the existing rows, keyed on the Task code.

10
00:01:09.308 --> 00:01:16.496
Now the job knows exactly which rows already exist, so it can update them in place instead of blindly appending.

11
00:01:17.496 --> 00:01:22.385
Beat two: it writes the new status by key, and you watch the cells flip.

12
00:01:22.685 --> 00:01:36.840
Enrollment drops to At Risk; the data cut moves to Watch and its date slips two days; the dependent dry-run tables date cascades with it; the spec ticks up to eighty-five percent; and one genuinely new row is appended.

13
00:01:37.140 --> 00:01:43.272
Every write is matched on the Task code — that idempotence is the whole reason this is safe to automate.

14
00:01:44.272 --> 00:01:52.586
Beats three and four: the job attaches last night's one-page status PDF to the data-cut row, and then it steps back.

15
00:01:52.886 --> 00:01:55.001
It does not send a single email.

16
00:01:55.301 --> 00:02:03.216
The instant the status cell changed to At Risk, the Smartsheet workflow you configured once fired the alert to the project manager.

17
00:02:03.516 --> 00:02:07.544
SAS or R wrote the fact; Smartsheet decided who to tell.

18
00:02:08.544 --> 00:02:10.896
Two safeguards make this trustworthy.

19
00:02:11.196 --> 00:02:17.944
Re-run the very same job and it reports zero rows added — matched by key, it can never duplicate.

20
00:02:18.244 --> 00:02:29.496
And when a stray, non-operational column tries to ride along, the allowlist blocks it in code, so no participant-level or reported clinical number can ever reach the cloud.

21
00:02:29.796 --> 00:02:35.669
The token is read from a secret at runtime, and the job is rate-limit aware and fails loud.

22
00:02:36.669 --> 00:02:37.977
That is the whole idea.

23
00:02:38.277 --> 00:02:47.960
Your tracker is always current, the alerts are automatic, and you never copy and paste a status again — all with validated SAS and R you already own.

24
00:02:48.260 --> 00:02:55.805
The macro library ships ready to use: drop in your sheet id, your key, and your allowlist, and schedule it.
